    <h3>1.	A brief introduction to Game Theory</h3>

    Game theory is a branch of applied mathematics which studies situations in which there is a conflict of interest between two parties. 
    It was pioneered in the 1940s by mathematician John von Neumann and economist Oskar Morgenstern, received significant contributions by researchers 
    and academics throughout the 1950s, and is an active field of research and applied science to this day. Game theory was brought into prominence in 
    the modern day, by the biographic film A Beautiful Mind, inspired by the life of Professor John Nash of Princeton University.  Nash, who was the 
    recipient of the Nobel Prize in Economic Sciences, contributed a number of concepts to Game Theory including the Nash Equilibrium and the Nash Bargaining Solution. 

    <p></p>Game theory is unlike other sciences in that it does not have a clearly defined and narrow scope. Its concepts and applications are useful in a range of 
    fields from economics, politics, psychology, diplomacy and war, and common parlor games from which it derives its name. Biologists have even linked Game theory 
    to Darwin’s theory of evolution in biological interactions of cooperation vs competition in nature.
    
</div>


<div id="divSection2" style="display:none" class="div-tutorial">
    <h3>2.	So, how does Game Theory work?</h3>
    Game theory studies decision-making between parties who have conflicting interests during which they can have one or more interactions. 
    It isn’t concerned with winning or losing, but evaluating strategies of optimal decision-making of independent and competing parties.

    <p></p>In a situation of conflicting interests, every interaction is defined as a <b>game</b> and any party making a decision is called a <b>player</b>.  
    Each player’s decisions will be motivated by a <b>payoff</b> within the game. The set of decisions they make to pursue an intended outcome is called a <b>strategy</b>.  
    Depending on the strategies available, the game may have many paths which can be depicted in a matrix or decision tree.  The <b>outcome</b> to a game can result from a 
    combination of player strategies which results as a terminal node of the decision tree.  The <b>solution</b> to a game is one in which both players use the most efficient 
    strategy to arrive at a terminal node of the decision tree.  

    <p></p><b>Nash Equilibrium</b> is the most common way to define a game’s solution: it is where each player has used the optimal strategy regardless of the strategy the opponent 
    has chosen, such that there are no better paths available by changing their own strategy.  We will discuss Nash’s equilibrium later…
</div>

