    <h3>4.	The game structure</h3>
    
    Games structure is determined by its characteristics. Common game characteristics include:
    <ul>
        <li><b>Number of players:</b> one-player, two-player… up to n-player</li>
        <li><b>Options per play:</b> is the number of decisions available to each player per turn</li>
        <li><b>Sequential vs simultaneous play:</b> whether both players play at the same time versus one after another</li>
        <li><b>Perfect vs imperfect information:</b> whether all the information is available during decision making time (like in chess where all the opponent pawns are visible), 
            versus only some information is available (like in poker where opponent cards are not visible)</li>
        <li><b>Constant sum vs variable sum:</b> the game of conflict is constant sum when the total payoff is static. A variable sum game can have varying payoffs depending on 
            strategy. Variable sum games are more suitable for cooperation strategies since higher payoffs are achievable if players act jointly for mutual benefit.</li>
    </ul>   
</div>


