    <h3>6.	Let’s try out an example…</h3>
    Let’s assume a scenario in which two career bank robbers are attempting a bank heist.  They are caught by the police during their escape.  The police want to 
    interrogate them to find out more about their scheme.  They decide to separate the robbers and question them individually.  In order to entice them, the police 
    offer a lighter sentence if each robber will betray their accomplice and confess against the other.

    <p></p>The offer from the police to both robbers is as follows:
    <ul>
        <li>If Robber A confesses and Robber B confesses, they both get 2 year prison time</li>
        <li>If Robber A confesses and Robber B stays silent, Robber A goes free and Robber B gets 3 years prison time</li>
        <li>If Robber A stays silent and Robber B confesses, then Robber A gets 3 years prison time and Robber B goes free</li>
        <li>If Robber A stays silent and Robber B stays silent, they both get 1 year prison time</li>
    </ul>
    
    Which option would you choose in this scenario?
