<div id="divSection8" style="display:none" class="div-tutorial">
    <h3>8.	Prisoner’s Dilemma in society…</h3>
    The prisoner’s dilemma was developed in 1950 by mathematicians Merrill Flood and Melvin Dresher during the Cold War.  Some have speculated the paradox was devised to simulate 
    strategic thinking during the Cold War.  Modern society is faced with many common dilemmas in which behaviour of individuals or organizations can be beneficial or harmful for 
    the greater good of society. The underlying motivation in many of these decisions is the payoff. 

    <p></p>One variation of the paradox is the <b>Tragedy of Commons</b>, in which a common resource is available for everyone but has to be consumed by all people in moderation to 
    ensure the resource is sustainable. The lumber and fishing industry are great examples. Each company can choose to consume resources in a sustainable manner which will be in 
    the interest of the greater group, or any company may choose to maximize their profit by deforesting or overfishing to serve their own self-interest.
    
    <p></p>Another variation is the <b>Behaviour of Cartles</b>, in which all members of the cartel cap price or production in order to ensure they can all be profitable.  Similar to 
    the previous variation, the market demand acts as the limited resources to regulate the payoff.  If one company undercuts the market price by decreasing its price or 
    increasing production, all companies within the cartel would have to do the same, which would result in lower profits.
    
</div>

