<div id="divSection10" style="display:none" class="div-tutorial">
    <h3>10.	The Nash Equilibrium</h3>
    According to game theory, the solution to the game may be different depending on the payoff and the decisions of the opponent.  However, in some situations the 
    strategy will always be the same regardless of the opponent’s game decisions.  This is referred to as the <b>dominant strategy</b>, which occurs when a player will 
    play the best strategy regardless of the opponent’s choices.

    <p></p>The <b>Nash Equilibrium</b>, named after Professor John Nash, is the most common way to define the solution to non-cooperative games. Unlike the dominant strategy, it acknowledges that each player considers opponent’s optimal strategy when formulating their own strategy. It states that a player has arrived at an optimal strategy such that they have nothing further to gain by changing their strategy regardless of the opponent’s choice to change strategies. When both players arrive at this state, it is referred to as Nash Equilibrium. 
